ormon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of   Morman  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Morman","meanings":["English: variant of   Moorman  .","Americanized form of German   Mormann  ."]}]},{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. If not simply an invention, it may have been devised as a feminine equivalent of   Alan   (of which it is an anagram), or a shortened form of   Alana .  It seems to have been first used by the American film actress  Lana Turner  (  1920–1995 ), whose original name was  Julia ."]}]},{"name":"Maryon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a medieval French diminutive form of   Marie  , introduced to Britain in the Middle Ages. In some places it was taken as a pet form of   Margaret   or   Margery .  As a male name, it is an altered form of the Continental male name <i>Marian</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>Marianus</i> (from   Marius  ), but is now rarely, if ever, used. It was the birth name of the American film star  John Wayne  (  1907–79 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Maryon Normon was born in 1520, in Rickmansworth, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir John Norman, was 38 and her mother, Lady Anne Birley, was 25. She married Robert Day in 1544, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents o